the domain set of coverageFunction shall be a subset of envelope and the domain of coverageFunction shall be defined by nativeCrs and the range of coverageFunction shall be rangeType

all partition sub-coverages shall conform to the super-coverage settings in nativeCrs, rangeType and allowedInterpolation and the coverage envelope shall be a superset of the union of all partition sub-coverage envelopes
Representation of some formula or algorithm to algorithmically determine domain set (i.e., direct positions) and range values.
some realization alternatives; concrete standards may or may not adopt these, and may provide further ones.
evaluate() implemented as pair of location list and value list, both ordered for correspondence. Hence, storage follows some linearization scheme.
Placeholder indicating that no interpolation is possible
for all element: geometry() returns Point
for all p in domainSet: value(p) obtained by linear interpolation
lowerBound, upperBound ontain exactly one coordinate component (i.e., dimension is 1)
resolution expresses difference between two axis coordinate values
for all components a in axisLabels: length(a) > 0

domainSet is a RectifiedGrid
which is equivalent to:
for all grid.axis: type is CV_RegularAxis and there is no grid.displacementAxisNest and there is no grid.algorithmicAxis
for all a in axisLabels: length(a) > 0

domainSet is a ReferenceableGrid
which is equivalent to:
at least one grid.axis is of type CV_IrregularAxis and there is no grid.displacementAxisNest and there is no grid.algorithmicAxis
for all p1, p2 in domainSet: p1=p2 => evaluate(p1)=evaluate(p2) and |evaluate(p1)|=|evaluate(p2)|=1
for all elements: geometry() is a Point defined by the grid

domainSet CRS is an ImageCRS
which is equivalent to:
for all grid.axis: type is CV_IndexAxis and there is no grid.displacementAxisNest and there is no grid.algorithmicAxis
coverage dimension shall be 2 or more

UML:Constraint.name: Grid is index, regular or irregular

UML:TaggedValue.value: for all axis a in domainSet.axis: type(a) is one of CV_IndexAxis, CV_RegularAxis, CV_IrregularAxis
for all DirectPosition p: evaluate(p) considers the regular hexagon having p as center.
for all axes: type of grid axis is CV_Index, CV_Regular
for all element: geometry() returns a Curve

The operation curve() shall return the CV_ValueCurve nearest to that direct position. The operation shall return an error message if the direct position is not close (i.e., within the distance specified by the tolerance parameter) to one of the CV_ValueCurves in the CV_SegmentedCurveCoverage.
for all element: geometry() returns Surface
for all surfaces s returned by geometry(): s is a triangle, i.e.: bounded by 3 curves connected by 3 points where each of these edges is a straight line
the set of all surfaces comprising the coverage constitute a Thiessen polygon.
for all element: geometry() returns a Solid

CV_InterpolationMethod is a list of codes that identify interpolation methods that may be used for evaluating continuous coverages.

A subtype of a feature. From the abstract specification, a Coverage is a two or more dimensional metaphor for features found on or near a portion of the Earth's Surface. Some examples of a Coverage would be a satellite image of a portion of the earth, a census tract for the city of New York and a DEM for a USGS 1x1 degree map sheet (Topic 6, OGC Abstract Specification, 1998)
A coverage is a subtype of a feature that has pairs of distinguished properties consisting of a geometry property and a function that is defined over the coordinate set that is defined (delineated) by the geometry (Herring, J. OGC Change Proposal 95-039r2)
The attribute domainExtent shall contain the extent of the spatiotemporal domain of the coverage. The data type EX_Extent, is defined in ISO 19103. Extents may be specified in both space and time.
If coverage function is contineous interpolation is permitted

The operation evaluate shall accept a DirectPosition as input and return the record of attribute values for that direct position. The data type Record is defined in ISO 19103. If the direct position passed is not in the spatiotemporal domain, then an error message shall be generated

A polygon whose boundaries define the area consisting of points that are closer to the center point than any other point in the defining set. The boundaries are the perpendicular bisectors of the lines between the points in the dual TIN. Also referred to as Voronoi Diagrams.
A segment is a 1-dimensional geometric object that has a beginning (start) and end point.
The geometry represented by the various offset vectors is in the image plane of the grid. For example, for orthorectified grids, these vectors are in a spatial reference system.
Default is row major, other values will be from enumeration to be determined at a later date.
